<TEXT>
the first criminal trial stemming from wall 
streets insider trading scandals faced the prospect of a second 
mistrial when a jury on saturday reported an 111 deadlock after 
eight days of deliberations 
a federal judge asked jurors in the gaf corp stock manipulation 
case to reconsider all evidence after they reported the split 
following more than 65 hours of deliberations 
the gaf case is the first trial based on the confessions of 
insider trader ivan boesky which led to the indictment and is 
considered a test of the governments ability to try wall street 
corruption 
your honor we need help there are 11 jurors who have come to 
a unanimous decision on counts one through eight and one juror who 
does not agree the jury reported in a note read in us district 
court in manhattan 
the panel reported that the juror said under no circumstances 
could he agree with the other jurors decision 
gaf two subsidiaries and vice chairman james t sherwin are 
charged with allegedly trying to boost the stock price of union 
carbide corp in 1986 shortly before selling a large block of 
shares they also were charged with securities fraud wire fraud and 
conspiracy among the eight counts 
under an instruction known as the allen charge us district 
judge mary johnson lowe asked the jurors to reconsider their 
positions in the securities fraud case and sent them back to 
deliberate 
before i declare a mistrial and discharge you i want to point 
out a few things to you lowe said it is desirable that if a 
verdict can be reached that this be done 
but lowe told the jury that they should not reverse positions 
solely to reach a verdict and left resolution to the conscientious 
judgment of each juror 
after hearing the judges statement the jury said it wanted to 
continue deliberating sunday afternoon 
the point of conflict among the jurors and whether the 11 
supported acquittal or conviction were not known 
a mistrial would be the second in the case lowe declared a 
mistrial jan 10 after ruling that the prosecution unintentionally 
withheld a key piece of evidence the second trial lasted six weeks 
gaf a wayne njbased chemical and building materials 
manufacturer faces a maximum fine of 12 million or 500000 on 
each of the eight counts sherwin 55 of princeton nj faces 40 
years in prison and a fine of up to 2 million 
the gaf case is being closely followed by wall street defense 
attorneys as a key indication of prosecutors ability to convince 
juries of wall street crimes and of the reliability of information 
supplied by boesky who is serving a threeyear term on insider 
trading charges 
the purpose of the alleged stock manipulation was to maximize 
gafs profits from the planned sale of a large block of union 
carbide stock after a failed takeover of the much larger chemical 
concern earlier in 1986 
gaf denied the charges in what became the first case to reach the 
trial phase in a wave of wall street corruption investigations by 
the manhattan us attorneys office 
the us attorneys office has brought charges in more than 50 
securities fraud cases since 1983 nearly all the claims however 
have involved civil charges criminal frauds to date including 
pending charges against drexel burnham lambert inc have been 
settled through plea bargains 
the government based its case on the testimony of los angeles 
broker boyd l jefferies an admitted felon expected to play a key 
role in other securities fraud cases as part of a plea arrangement 
with the government 
