bargain prices for coveted airport gates and 
computer reservation systems millions in loans from a debtswamped 
airline to its growing sister moneylosing deals to buy fuel from 
the parent 
in court papers eastern airlines recalcitrant pilots make a 
strong case that texas air corp chairman frank lorenzo has plotted 
to suck easterns blood to buoy nonunion continental airlines a 
key issue as the saga of the strikedecimated carrier moves through 
bankruptcy proceedings 
either a sophisticated asset stripping scheme is under way or 
management is incompetent the pilots state in documents filed in 
us bankruptcy court last week 
the pilots cite alleged bargain sales nogain loans and 
moneylosing arrangements they say have undermined parent texas 
airs claim that its affiliated airlines are separate entities they 
say lorenzos management clearly benefited continental and texas air 
at easterns detriment 
eastern which was losing money long before lorenzo arrived in 
1986 says it transacted aboveboard fairmarket deals among 
subsidiaries with no illicit intermingling of eastern and 
continental blood 
nonetheless a 59page court brief filed last week by the air 
line pilots association provides illuminating details that at least 
raise major questions about eastern managements behavior 
the brief culls information from securities and exchange 
commission filings federal court testimony a transportation 
department report and company financial records to make the case 
that eastern and continental are deeply interwoven 
the most striking deal the red flag on the bull in the 
bullring in the words of one aviation analyst was the 1987 
transfer of easterns coveted computerized reservation system to 
continental for 100 million 
at the time the system was worth at least triple that amount 
moreover debtswamped eastern didnt get a 100 million cash 
infusion from the deal which it badly needed to support daytoday 
operations instead it got 100 million in notes bearing 6 percent 
interest payable in full in the year 2012 
analysts have questioned the financial wisdom of transferring the 
computerized reservation system to its new sister similar networks 
soon after fetched 280 million 500 million and 650 million 
eastern maintains it couldnt afford to upgrade its network in a 
highly competitive battle for travel agents who book tickets 
through airlinerun computers eastern says it was paying 130 
million a year to operate the network money it now pays to texas 
air for a better product 
the question of whether eastern and continental have been kept 
separate is central to the bankruptcy proceedings 
a judge ultimately could decide whether lorenzo allowed eastern 
to languish and refused to merge the two subsidiaries in an attempt 
to destroy easterns unions texas air wants to avoid placing its 
assets on the line to cover easterns more than 3 billion in 
liabilities 
by keeping the companies separate lorenzo doesnt get the two 
groups together to be unionized said a new york aviation lawyer 
who asked not to be identified if he put the two together he 
would face a situation where if he allowed enough parity of 
employees that would force an election 
then lorenzo has a completely unionized property which is what 
he got out of five years ago 
the pilots court brief also alleges the following action damaged 
eastern 
eastern loaned 40 million to continental last spring at the 
same time it was seeking an internal revenue service waiver on a 
105 million contribution to its pension fund eastern says the loan 
was repaid 
for almost two years eastern failed to demand a noninterest 
bearing 16 million payment due for mergerrelated expenses from 
texas air the inaction cost the airline about 28 million a year 
in lost interest earnings eastern called it a bookkeeping 
transaction that has since been paid 
in march 1987 eastern paid texas air 25 million for a note 
worth 30 million owned by nearly bankrupt people express which 
texas air had previously acquired texas air made 44 million on 
the deal the pilots called it a senseless investment since people 
express had no creditworthiness and eastern needed to conserve cash 
eastern paid 22 million to continental for strikerelated 
services in december 1987 and another 19 million last fall for 
similar services that have not been used eastern maintains the 
money was wellspent 
continental the pilots claim disproportionate gained from a 
merger of sales offices with eastern in january 1987 eastern 
brought in 166 offices while continental contributed 27 the 
arrangement was dissolved last december 
continental paid 11 million to eastern for 11 newark 
international airport gates allegedly worth twice as much the court 
papers compare the deal with easterns 1986 sale of eight charlotte 
nc gates to piedmont airlines for 25 million eastern says it 
got the market price 
a fuel purchase agreement with texas air costs eastern about 18 
million annually but provides no apparent savings the papers state 
eastern claims it saves 6 million a year texas air claims the 
arrangement merges purchases of eastern and continental giving them 
greater clout with suppliers 
